BAE, Barclays, Barratt, Rio Tinto: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t
-- 
2011-07-14T06:54:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-13/barclays-plc-marks-spencer-rbs-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  Futures contracts on the FTSE 100 Index slid 0.7 percent to
5,822 at 7:53 a.m. in  London . Yesterday, the FTSE 100 gained
37.47, or 0.6 percent, to 5,906.43. The FTSE All-Share Index
rose 0.6 percent to 3,076.55, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index
advanced 0.7 percent to 2,908.19.  BAE Systems Plc (BA/ LN): JPMorgan Chase & Co. downgraded
the shares to “neutral” from “overweight”.  Separately, Armor Holdings Inc., a unit of the U.K.’s
biggest defense and airspace contractor, agreed to pay $16
million to resolve U.S. claims that it bribed a United Nations
official to win contracts before BAE acquired the company. The
shares climbed 2.3 percent to 305.8 pence.  Barclays Plc (BARC)  : Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed  Al Nahyan ,
a member of  Abu Dhabi ’s royal family, decreased his stake in the
bank to less than 7 percent, Barclays said in a statement. The
stock rose 0.2 percent to 228 pence.  Barratt Developments Plc (BDEV)  : Britain’s largest
homebuilder by volume will report full-year operating profit of
about 135 million pounds ($217.9 million), according to a
statement today. That compares with 90.1 million pounds a year
earlier. The stock gained 1.9 percent to 111.2 pence.  BP Plc (BP/)  : The international  oil company  said it
extinguished a fire on its Valhall production platform off the
coast of Norway and shut down the field. The shares increased
0.7 percent to 456.5 pence.  British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc (BSY)  : U.K. Business
Secretary Vince Cable said that  News Corp . will probably not
revive its bid for Britain’s largest listed broadcaster.  Separately, former Prime Minister  Gordon Brown  urged U.K.
media regulator Ofcom to investigate whether News Corp. is a
“fit and proper” company to hold its 39 percent stake in
BSkyB. The stock climbed 2 percent to 705.5 pence.  Irish Life & Permanent Plc (IPM ID): Ireland’s biggest life
insurer received a proposal from shareholders to extend the
company’s July 31 capitalization deadline, it said in a
statement. The shares slumped 5 percent to 3.8 euro cents.  Marks & Spencer Group Plc (MKS)  : Chief Executive Officer
 Marc Bolland  said he received “big support” from shareholders
for his plans to expand online and in markets outside the U.K.
The stock dropped 2.5 percent to 363.8 pence.  Rio Tinto  Group Plc (RIO LN): The world’s second-biggest
mining company reported second-quarter iron-ore production of
48.9 million tons compared with 43.6 million tons a year
earlier. The miner also reported a 24 percent drop in copper
output. The shares added 1.2 percent to 4,441 pence.  Rolls-Royce Holdings Plc (RR/ LN): JPMorgan Chase & Co.
upgraded its stance on the U.K. engine maker to “overweight”
from “neutral”. The shares advanced 2.3 percent to 651 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in London at 
 bgatt@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
